Rakuen's disaster-recovery doctrine was partly shaped by the Oathbound March's failure mode: crisis infrastructure that outlasts the crisis it was built for.
When the plague receded, the processing infrastructure had no built-in transition to peacetime operation. It continued operating.
Rakuen's modern processing framework includes explicit transition protocols: when crisis metrics fall below threshold, crisis infrastructure begins managed drawdown — a mandatory obligation, not an administrative option. This is called the March provision in Rakuen's charter.
Rakuen's analysis: the March's dead perform their defined function with perfect fidelity. The function is the wrong one for the current context, but the fidelity is not in question.
Less extreme versions of this failure mode exist in every city: offices enforcing emergency regulations after the emergency has passed, levy structures active after the route they supported was abandoned. Rakuen's Garden Ledger tracks these as post-mandate operations.

