Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw maintains the Oathbound March as the definitive case for oath-design requirements in institutional charter.
Valid oaths, if not designed with appropriate scope limitations, can become valid obligations to wrong actions.
The Shrine's oath certification process requires oath-takers to demonstrate understanding of the oath's scope: what it covers, what it does not cover, and what conditions would make it inapplicable.
The March's oath was sworn by personnel who understood its scope in the moment but was not documented with the conditions under which it would become inapplicable.
When the conditions changed — the Crown fell, the Plague Mandate was superseded, the frontier context dissolved — no documented scope-limitation applied. The oath continued.
Mafdet now requires that all institutional oaths include a scope-expiration condition: either a time limit, a mandate metric, or a designated authority with dissolution power. The oathbound dead in Shadowmere are the Shrine's most frequently cited example of what happens when this requirement is omitted.

